le American poets in the second half of the twentieth century. Their association, played out in their poems and in an extraordinary exchange of letters, was based on a sense of the visionary imagination informing the direction and shape of the poet. However, they had a falling out during the Vietnam crisis over the relationship between poetry and politics, between the private and public responsibilities of the poet. Such issues are vital not only to their poetry and the poetry of that period but to contemporary poetry as well. A distinguished group of critics, led by Albert Gelpi and Robert J. Bertholf, examines the issues that drew Levertov and Duncan together, and split them apart, in a book that has the openness and coherence of an urgent, contemporary dialogue about the form and meaning of poetry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Poetry.2bisacsh1 aBertholf, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertholf, Robert J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCapinha, Graça, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewey, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelstiner, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelpi, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGelpi, Albert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerrera, Jose Rodriguez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollenberg, Donna Krolik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnston, Devin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacey, Paul A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMillier, Brett, econtribu